Linear Regression

Linear regression is used to model the relationship between a numeric outcome variable and one or more features by fitting a linear equation to the data. The model estimates coefficients that minimize the sum of squared residuals. Linear Regression is one of the oldest predictive modeling techniques.

Use Cases

  • Predicting housing prices from square footage and location
  • Estimating insurance premiums from age and health indicators
  • Forecasting company revenue based on marketing spend
  • Estimating blood pressure based on age and BMI
  • Forecasting electricity demand from temperature and time of day

Strengths

  • Well-understood and extensively used
  • Fast and computationally efficient
  • Easy to interpret and communicate

Weaknesses

  • Assumes a linear relationship between features and outcome
  • Sensitive to multicollinearity, outliers, and missing data
  • Cannot capture complex non-linear interactions unless transformed
  • Makes a number of assumptions such as constant variance and normally distributed errors

Overview

This note will demonstrate the use of Linear Regression to estimate earnings based on characteristics of individuals. The note will examine simple regression with a numeric feature, simple regression with a categorical feature, multiple regression with an interaction, and multiple regression with a combination of numerical and categorical features. All models will be estimated using functions from StatsModels as it provides statistical details. For an implementation using Scikit-Learn, look at the other note on Linear Regression.

Data Description

Earning data is derived from a survey of individuals on a multitude of characteristics including demographics, physical characteristics, health, well-being and earning. (Original Data Source: Regression and Other stories, by Andrew Gelman, Jennifer Hill, and Avi Vekhtari). We are interested in examining the factors that influence annual earning (earn) and predicting an individuals annual earning.

Data consists of characteristics of a set of employees and their annual earning. Variables included are:

  • earn: Annual earning in dollars
  • age: Age in years
  • gender: male, female
  • height: Height in inches
  • weight: Weight in pounds
  • ethnicity: White, African American, Hispanic, Asian
  • education: Years of education
  • walk: Frequency of taking a walk (in a week)
  • exercise: Frequency of strenuous exercise (in a week)
  • smokenow: Smoke seven or more cigarettes a week (1 = Yes, 2 = No)
  • tense: Days felt tense or anxious

Read Data

import pandas as pd
data = pd.read_csv('earning.csv')

Data Partition

Evaluating a model using data to estimate it risks overfitting the model to the data used to build it. For this reason, it is best to evaluate the model using a different dataset. Since getting a fresh dataset for evaluating a model may be costly, time consuming and in some cases impossible, it is common to split the data into a train and test sample, estimating the model using the train and evaluating it using the test.

Let us start by splitting the data into a train and test sample such that 70% of the data is in the train sample. For reproducibility, will set random state to 1031.

train = data.sample(frac = 0.7,random_state=617)
test = data.drop(labels = train.index)

Simple Regression: age

As people get older, they gain experience and get better at doing their job. Therefore, it is reasonable to expect age to be positively related to earn. We can visualize this using a scatterplot. Is there a discernible trend?

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
sns.scatterplot(data = train, 
                x = 'age', 
                y = 'earn', 
                color='steelblue',
                s=10)
plt.show()

Correlation

Correlation is a measure of linear association between two continuous variables. We can examine the strength of association between these two variables using pearson product-moment correlation.

train.loc[:,['age','earn']].corr()
age earn
age 1.000000 0.060472
earn 0.060472 1.000000

.corr() in pandas is a convenient method for extracting pearson correlations but it does not provide p-values for the coefficients, so will turn to the scipy library.

from scipy.stats import pearsonr
pearsonr(train['age'],train['earn'])
PearsonRResult(statistic=np.float64(0.060471608039428144), pvalue=np.float64(0.03253201748393041))

Correlation results indicate a significant positive relationship between age and earn. However, the correlation coefficient does not specify direction. Common sense suggests age would influence earn and not the other way. So, next we specify a directional relationship using a simple regression.

Fit Model

Two of the popular Python libraries for implementing linear regression are Scikit-Learn and StatsModels. Scikit-Learn which has a strong machine learning orientation does not provide statistical details that are critical in understanding Linear Regression. For this reason, we will introduce the topic using StatsModels.

from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
reg = ols('earn~age', data = train)
model1 = reg.fit()
model1.params
Intercept    40923.073187
age            188.105851
dtype: float64
print('Estimated Regression Equation:\n', 'earn = ', model1.params.loc['Intercept'], ' + ', model1.params.loc['age'],'*age')
Estimated Regression Equation:
 earn =  40923.07318713078  +  188.10585128063107 *age

Predict

Model parameter estimates can be used to make predictions for each observation. For instance, to predict the earn of the first respondent whose age is 24, simply substitute the value of age in the above equation.

print(40895.96136415939 + 168.29888213808906 * 24)
44935.134535473524

Of course, it is not practical to do this for each value to be predicted. So, we rely on the .predict() method.

model1.predict()[0]
np.float64(47318.67213067224)

Let us examine the predictions of the first ten respondents

pd.DataFrame({'age': train.age, 
              'predictions': model1.predict(), 
              'earn': train.earn}).head(10)

The quality of predictions can be evaluated by comparing the true value of earn to predictions.

  • R2: Popular statistical index
  • SSE: Sum of squared errors
  • RMSE: Generates an error estimate in the units of the data
RMSE
import numpy as np
pred = model1.predict()
rmse1 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(pred - train.earn)))
rmse1
np.float64(54141.2543281431)
SSE
sse1 = np.sum(np.square(pred - train.earn))
sse1
np.float64(3664094275280.8423)
R-Squared
r_squared1 = model1.rsquared
r_squared1
np.float64(0.0036568153788744118)

Inference

Regression models are useful not just for prediction but also for explanation. Regression model summary contains information on statistical significance of the overall model and regression coefficients. A p-value of less than alpha indicates the coefficient is different from 0. Unless otherwise stated, we will use an alpha of 0.05.

The F-statistic of 4.580 has a p-value of 0.0325 which is less than 0.05. This indicates the overall model is statistically significant. Since age is the only predictor, not surprisingly, the coefficient of age is also significantly different from 0 (p = 0.033 < 0.05).

Furthermore, the coefficient of age indicates the nature of the relationship with age. Specifically, the coefficient reflects of age reflects the change in earn for a one year increase in age. In other words, with every passing year, one would expect earning to change by 188.1059 dollars. By extension, a ten year age difference will correspond to an earning difference of 1881.059 dollars.

This can be verified by computing the predicted earn for two consecutive years, say 35 and 36.

age_35 = pd.DataFrame({'const':[1],'age':[35]})
age_36 = pd.DataFrame({'const':[1],'age':[36]})
model1.predict(age_36) - model1.predict(age_35)
0    188.105851
dtype: float64

3. Simple Regression, Categorical Variable: gender

Let us examine the relationship between gender and earn. Since gender is categorical, we will examine the relationship using a bar chart instead of a scatterplot.

sns.barplot(data = train, 
                y = 'gender', 
                x = 'earn', 
                hue = 'gender',orient = 'h')
plt.show()

Fit

Next, estimate a regression using gender as predictor of earn. Since gender is a categorical variable with two levels, ols() will automatically dummy code the variable setting the first level as reference.

reg = ols('earn ~ gender', data = train)
model3 = reg.fit()

Predict

r_squared3 = model3.rsquared
r_squared3
np.float64(0.09079695073221739)
pred = model3.predict()
rmse3 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(pred - train.earn)))
rmse3
np.float64(51719.4952450114)

4. Simple Regression, Categorical Predictor: ethnicity

Let us examine the relationship between ethnicity and earn using a box plot.

sns.boxplot(data = train, 
                x= 'ethnicity', 
                y = 'earn', 
                hue = 'ethnicity')
plt.show()

Fit

Estimate a regression using ethnicity as predictor of earn. Since ethnicity is a categorical variable, ols() will automatically create k-1 dummy variables where k is the number of levels of ethnicity. The first level based on alphabetical order will serve as reference level.

reg = ols('earn ~ ethnicity', data = train)
model4 = reg.fit()

Predict

model4.pvalues
Intercept                4.839267e-16
ethnicity[T.Asian]       7.624861e-01
ethnicity[T.Hispanic]    6.209750e-01
ethnicity[T.White]       3.646812e-02
dtype: float64

All three dummy variables are non-significant. The analyst community is divided on the issue of whether to use non-significant variables for prediction. Most statistically oriented analysts would drop non-significant variables. But, there are some who believe that non-significant variables may still aid in prediction. Accordingly, we are using it for predictions.

r_squared4 = model4.rsquared
r_squared4
np.float64(0.008061431917691153)
pred = model4.predict()
rmse4 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(pred - train.earn)))
rmse4
np.float64(54021.448417021566)

Inference

The dummy variables in the model summary reflect the contrast of the level the variable name and those who are African American. All three dummy variables are non-significant indicating there no difference in earning between those who are African American and any of the other three ethnic groups.

model5 = reg.fit()

Model summary indicates a statistically significant interaction effect of weight and gender. To gain more insight on the nature and meaning of this interaction, we will plot the results.

Direction of interaction shows the effect of weight on earn has very different effects for males and females. For males, an increase in weight is tied to an increase in earn, while for females the opposite is true.

6. Multiple Regression: All predictors

Generally speaking, adding more meaningful predictors will improve the quality of predictions. So, we are going to include all the predictors in our next model. Since this model uses multiple predictors, it is called multiple regression.

Fit

reg = ols('earn ~ age + gender + height + weight + ethnicity + education + walk + exercise + smokenow + tense', data = train)
model6 = reg.fit()

Predict

r_squared6 = model6.rsquared
r_squared6
np.float64(0.20028177721365903)
pred = model6.predict()
rmse6 = np.sqrt(np.mean(np.square(pred - train.earn)))
rmse6
np.float64(48505.650370861804)

Inference

The model summary provides us information to explain the predictions. You will notice the inferences from multiple regression are not the same as for simple regression.

The coefficients for significant variables can be interpreted in a manner similar to simple regression with the caveat of ceteris paribus. For instance, one year of education corresponds to an increase in earn of $6471.9786 while holding all other variables constant.

Summary

In this note, we examined implementation of Linear Regression for prediction and inference with

  • one numeric feature
  • one categorical feature
  • an interaction between two features
  • multiple features

All models were estimated using functions from StatsModels to emphasize statistical details.
